# Neutrophil Metabolic Reprogramming Pipeline

A computational pipeline for characterizing condition-specific metabolic states in human neutrophils using genome-scale metabolic (GSM) modeling and multi-method machine learning feature importance analysis.

---

## Overview

This pipeline integrates transcriptomic data with genome-scale metabolic models to reconstruct condition-specific flux distributions across four neutrophil states (Normal, G-CSF-treated, HSCT, and PDAC-associated). A bootstrap sampling strategy generates a robust feature matrix from parsimonious flux balance analysis (pFBA), which is then subjected to a four-method consensus ranking framework to identify the most discriminative metabolic reactions. Solute carrier (SLC) family transporters emerged as the dominant discriminative feature class in both the primary and an independent validation cohort.

A full description of the methods, results, and biological interpretation is available in the associated dissertation chapter and manuscript [CITATION].

---

## Key Findings

- SLC family transporters are the top-ranked discriminative metabolic feature class across all four methods in the primary cohort (Montaldo et al., Nature Immunology)
- Vitamin E metabolism (gamma-tocopherol, gamma-tocotrienol) differentiates G-CSF-treated from HSCT neutrophils
- PDAC-associated neutrophils display globally elevated metabolic activity with restricted metabolite exchange fluxes
- In the independent sepsis validation cohort (GSE167363, Qiu et al.), SLC-associated reactions account for 85% of the top consensus-ranked features, compared to 25% in the primary cohort
- LDA resolved to a rank-1 solution in the primary cohort, indicating that G-CSF, HSCT, and PDAC conditions diverge from Normal along a shared metabolic axis

